In the original proposal, we see patterns by alanjds:

"""
main_resources/ + {?fields=} + {?filter: __eq= | __ne= | ...} + {?additonal args like : signature= | request_target_for_query_str}

main_resources/{master_pk}
main_resources/{master_pk}/slave_resources/
main_resources/{master_pk}/slave_resources/{slave_pk}
"""

Actually, I do personally believe that is not enough:

(1) one kind resource might intercept another kind of resource
(2) {master_pk} can be repalced by '/'(group select) '{master_selector}'

Hence we have relational pattern for automatic resources generation:

master_resource/                                                                  {priority 1}
master_resource/{master_pk}/                                              {priority 2}
master_resource/related_resources/                                      {priority 3}, plural keyword 'related_resources' is reserved
master_resource/{master_pk}/related_resources/{relate_res_pk or slector expression}

Hello,
I would like to validate models more strictly in the POST apis, and prevent the sending of additional properties.

I found a workaround, explained below. 

Would it make sense to add this "additionalProperties: False" in the schema creation of a model ? (1 line)
Or with an additional option for a "strict" validation ? (more complex. I do not know how to proceed)

(This change would be in model.py/Model._schema) 

What do you think ?
Thanks a lot

```
api = Namespace('api')

ITEM_POST_INPUT = api.model('Item Input', {
    'name': fields.String(required=True),
    'label': fields.String(required=True),
})

@ns.route('items', endpoint='items_list')
class item_list_endpoint(Resource):
    @ns.expect(ITEM_POST_INPUT, validate=True)
    def post(self):
        '''Create new object'''
       pass
```

I want to accept strictly objects with "name" and "label" properties, both required.
But, if I send an object with additional properties, it is validated : { name: "name", label: "label", format: "xxx" }

I have found a workaround, by overiding the __schema__ of the models created in the namespace.

```
// Iterate all models of namespace
for m, v in api.models.iteritems():
    v.__schema__["additionalProperties"] = False

// I think I can do also: 
ITEM_POST_INPUT.__schema__["additionalProperties"] = False
```

It works and does not accept additional properties during validation.
But I find this workaround ugly...

