Hi Thomas,

I am working with add-path currently and am running across an issue with the withdraw JSON string EXABGP is logging to a file that Python can't parse correctly.

It is only with the withdraw message:

Here is the log line in JSON format:

```
{ "exabgp": "3.4.8", "time": 1472427836, "host" : "epe-demo-server", "pid" : "11896", "ppid" : "11893", "counter": 34, "type": "update", "neighbor": { "ip": "10.164.2.58", "address": { "local": "10.164.1.177", "peer": "10.164.2.58"}, "asn": { "local": "64512", "peer": "64512"}, "message": { "update": { "withdraw": { "ipv4 unicast": { "14.0.0.0/8": { "path-information": "0.0.0.1" }, "14.0.0.0/8": { "path-information": "0.0.0.2" } } } } }} }
```

Running it through a JSON Validator there is a warning error that Duplicate key, names should be unique.[Code 23, Structure 81] - the 14.0.0.0/8 key

```
{
   "exabgp":"3.4.8",
   "time":1472427836,
   "host":"epe-demo-server",
   "pid":"11896",
   "ppid":"11893",
   "counter":34,
   "type":"update",
   "neighbor":{
      "ip":"10.164.2.58",
      "address":{
         "local":"10.164.1.177",
         "peer":"10.164.2.58"
      },
      "asn":{
         "local":"64512",
         "peer":"64512"
      },
      "message":{
         "update":{
            "withdraw":{
               "ipv4 unicast":{
                  "14.0.0.0/8":{
                     "path-information":"0.0.0.1"
                  },
                  "14.0.0.0/8":{
                     "path-information":"0.0.0.2"
                  }
               }
            }
         }
      }
   }
}
```

As a result Python (json.loads) Parses this string as below:

```
{u'counter': 34,
 u'exabgp': u'3.4.8',
 u'host': u'epe-demo-server',
 u'neighbor': {u'address': {u'local': u'10.164.1.177',
                            u'peer': u'10.164.2.58'},
               u'asn': {u'local': u'64512', u'peer': u'64512'},
               u'ip': u'10.164.2.58',
               u'message': {u'update': {u'withdraw': {u'ipv4 unicast': {u'14.0.0.0/8': {u'path-information': u'0.0.0.2'}}}}}},
 u'pid': u'11896',
 u'ppid': u'11893',
 u'time': 1472427836,
 u'type': u'update'}
```

All other update messages are fine - and sometimes I get separate withdraw messages for withdraw and that works fine too - because obviously there are no duplicate keys.

Is this a known issue - can EXABGP split this into 2 updates?  Not sure on the exact method producing the original string above, but python parsing doesn't like it (no error (as the format's valid), just only stores the last value because its not unique)

Thanks
Russ

##### ISSUE TYPE

- Bug Report

##### OS
- Debian 9
- CentOS 7

##### VERSION
```
root@exabgp:~# INTERPRETER=python /mnt/hgfs/devtools/exabgp/sbin/exabgp --version
ExaBGP : 4.0.2-1c737d99
Python : 2.7.13 (default, Jan 19 2017, 14:48:08)  [GCC 6.3.0 20170118]
Uname  : Linux exabgp 4.9.0-3-amd64 #1 SMP Debian 4.9.30-2+deb9u3 (2017-08-06) x86_64
Root   : /mnt/hgfs/devtools/exabgp
```

##### ENVIRONMENT 

```
root@exabgp:~# INTERPRETER=python /mnt/hgfs/devtools/exabgp/sbin/exabgp --di

[exabgp.daemon]
drop = false
user = 'root'

[exabgp.tcp]
bind = '[0.0.0.0]'
```

##### CONFIGURATION
```
template {
  neighbor all {
    router-id 192.168.3.9;
    local-as 64400;
    hold-time 20;
    capability {
      graceful-restart;
    }
  }
}

process foo {
  run '/mnt/hgfs/devtools/exabgp/bin/showadjrib.py';
  encoder text;
}

neighbor 192.168.3.8 {
 inherit all;
  local-address 192.168.3.9;
  family {
    ipv4 unicast;
  }
  peer-as 64300;
}
```

##### SUMMARY

when using `show adj-rib out extensive` *neighbor* is printed twice:

```
neighbor neighbor 192.168.3.8 local-ip 192.168.3.9 local-as 64400 peer-as 64300 router-id 192.168.3.9 family-allowed in-open ipv4 unicast 192.168.4.0/24 next-hop self
```

##### STEPS TO REPRODUCE
Given the previous config and a peer configured properly, sending
`announce route 192.168.4.0/24 next-hop self` to exabgp and then
`show adj-rib out extensive`

prints out
```
neighbor neighbor 192.168.3.8 local-ip 192.168.3.9 local-as 64400 peer-as 64300 router-id 192.168.3.9 family-allowed in-open ipv4 unicast 192.168.4.0/24 next-hop self
```


##### EXPECTED RESULTS

```
neighbor 192.168.3.8 local-ip 192.168.3.9 local-as 64400 peer-as 64300 router-id 192.168.3.9 family-allowed in-open ipv4 unicast 192.168.4.0/24 next-hop self
```
##### ACTUAL RESULTS
```
neighbor neighbor 192.168.3.8 local-ip 192.168.3.9 local-as 64400 peer-as 64300 router-id 192.168.3.9 family-allowed in-open ipv4 unicast 192.168.4.0/24 next-hop self
```

##### IMPORTANCE
people implementing client that read the result from the api will have to work around it.

