    }

    LOGW("Scene::CleanUpCollisionDetection(): Clean up collision world ...");
    if (bt_collision_world) { delete bt_collision_world; bt_collision_world = nullptr; }
    // delete mSolver;

    LOGW("Scene::CleanUpCollisionDetection(): Clean up broadphase ...");
    if (bt_broadphase)      { delete bt_broadphase; bt_broadphase = nullptr; }

    LOGW("Scene::CleanUpCollisionDetection(): Clean up dispatcher ...");
    if (bt_dispatcher)      { delete bt_dispatcher; bt_dispatcher = nullptr; }

    LOGW("Scene::CleanUpCollisionDetection(): Clean up collision configuration ...");
    if (bt_collision_configuration) { delete bt_collision_configuration; bt_collision_configuration = nullptr; }

    LOGW("Scene::CleanUpCollisionDetection(): SURVIVED cleaning up collision configuration!");
}`

Think somehow something is getting delete'd twice?

We are teaching a large C++ class using Jupyter and the xeus-cling notebook, which gives them a very nice learning environment. However, when learning loops, our students often screw up and get infinite loops such as:
```
int i = 1;
while (i < 10) {
    cout << i << endl;
} 
```
On our lower-end machines (maybe 8 years old, Ubuntu, firefox) the browser usually freezes after a few seconds; not killing the server immediately results in the machine freezing due to swaping with no option than rebooting. Not a nice learning experience for them :-)

On my machine with 8Gb of memory, the browser copes with the load for quite some time thanks to the data throttling, leaving me plenty of time to stop the kernel. I can reproduce the freezing though by writing large enough strings at each step (see [attached notebook](https://gist.github.com/nthiery/24e2a29185bbe74d52ef62d89b1218db) ).

The Sage notebook had a very convenient way to handle large outputs by showing only the first and last lines, with `...` in the middle, together with a way for the user to request the full output. In the Jupyter world the latter feature might be hard to implement, which is ok. On the other hand e.g. discarding output data would be better than crashing.

Of course the difficulty  is to set good default values, for the throttling threshold, the discarding limit, ...

Related: #1529
cc: @LoicGouarin, @SylvainCorlay, @takluyver

Hi, is there a possibility of setting limit to the querysets, and then including in the response result count of the each queryset in the list, when `flat` is set to `False`?
Here's an example showing that:

```
[
    {
        'play' : [
                {'genre': 'Comedy', 'title': "A Midsummer Night's Dream", 'pages': 350},
                {'genre': 'Tragedy', 'title': "Romeo and Juliet", 'pages': 300}
            ],
        count: 20
    },
